RESULTS: The average resection length was 110 mm (80-154) and the average 
follow-up was 106.7 months (65-141). Bone union achieved in all patients with an 
average duration of 7.6 months (5-10). The average HHS, MSTS score and gluteus 
medius strength at one-year follow-up were 88.0 (80-94), 25.2 (22-28) and 4 
(3-5), respectively. While at the last follow-up, the HHS, MSTS score and 
gluteus medius strength were 83.0 (48-100), 24.0 (10-30) and 4 (2-5), 
respectively. Five intraoperative fractures were fixed with cerclage wires. Two 
postoperative periprosthetic and prosthetic fractures received a revision. Three 
local recurrent patients received a secondary surgery. One of these three lung 
metastatic patients underwent lung metastatic tumor resection. Another two 
patients were diagnosed with both bone and lung metastases, only one of them 
underwent amputation. Two greater trochanteric fractures received no treatment. 
There were10 severe, 3 moderate and 5 mild allograft resorptions without 
treatment.
CONCLUSION: Uncemented APC is a reliable reconstruction for neoplastic bone 
defect of the proximal femur, especially for the young patient who expected 
long-life expectancy and good function. Though allograft resorption and 
trochanteric fracture are the common complications, they seem no effect on the 
function.

